  "texts": [
    "C. Numerical MethodWe use the time-dependent Lanczos method [58] to simulate the time evolution of our many-body system and full exact diagonalization to compute thermal expectation values [59,60].",
    "We use periodic boundary conditions in all simulations.We exploit symmetries, including total magnetization S z total, conservation of the number of conductions electrons N e, and translational invariance [60].",
    "The latter symmetry arises from the invariance of the Hamiltonian under lattice translations, i.e., eigenstates of Ĥ can also be chosen as eigenstates of the lattice translation operator T, with eigenvalues e iK, where the crystal momentum K = 2πn/L (n = 0, 1,..., L -1) labels the different momentum sectors.In general, the dimension of the Hilbert space for a Kondo-lattice model with L sites, N c conduction electrons, and total magnetization S z total can be written as a sum over all possible spin-up electron configurations asdim(H) = Nc N ↑ =0 L N ↑ L N c -N ↑ L L ↑.",
    "(15)Here N ↑ denotes the number of spin-up conduction electrons, andL ↑ = 1 2 [L + 2S z total -2N ↑ + N c](16)is the number of localized spins with S z ℓ = 1/2.",
    "When the translation invariance is imposed, the size of the Hilbert space is reduced by roughly a factor of L. This reduction is exact when all the representative states have a periodicity equal to the full system size."
